12.1%( 2006)\n\n'''Imports - commodities:'''<ref name=uzstat/>\nmachinery and equipment 40.3%, chemical products 15.0%, metals 10.4%, food products 8.1%, energy products 4.3%, services 9.1% (2006)\n\n'''Reserves of foreign exchange & gold:'''\n$5.6 billion (Dec. 2007 est.)\n\n'''Exchange rates:'''\n* UZS per USD - 1,865 (early 2012)\n* UZS (s'om) per USD - 9,397 (2019)\n\n* UZS per EUR - 2,900\n* UZS per EUR - 10,389 (Sept 2019)\n\n'''Current economy growth (6 months of 2009)'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://traveluzbekistan.info/index.php/uzbek-economy/51-2009-results.html |title=On results of socio-economic development of the Republic of Uzbekistan in the first half of 2009 |access-date=2009-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120100633/http://traveluzbekistan.info/index.php/uzbek-economy/51-2009-results.html |archive-date=2012-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''GDP growth'' +8,2%\n* ''Volume of industrial production'' +9.1%\n* ''Volume of agricultural production'' +4,6%\n\n==See also==\n* [[Special economic zone#Uzbekistan|Special economic zones of Uzbekistan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20130927153018/http://bs-agro.com/index.php/news/other-countries/6715-uzbekistan-joins-cis-fta ''Uzbekistan: Accession of Uzbekistan to the Free Trade Area (FTA) CIS'']\n\n{{Asia in topic|Economy of}}\n\n[[Category:Economy of Uzbekistan| ]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2), 1992-2008 \u2192 1992\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economy_of_Uzbekistan"}
{"title_page": "Krvna osveta", "text_new": "{{for|the album by Dvorska Luda|Krvna osveta (album)}}\n{{redirect|Zakletva|the album by Stoja|Zakletva (album)}}\n'''Krvna Osveta''' ({{lang-sr|\u041a\u0440\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430}}, '''''[[Blood feud]]''''') is a [[law]] of [[Feud|vendetta]] among South Slavic peoples in [[Montenegro]] and [[Herzegovina]], practised by [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]] and [[Bosniaks]] throughout history since medieval times. It is an oath of revenge for vendetta, meaning that the person must take revenge on whomever killed his relative by killing the murderer or one of the murderer's close relatives.<ref>Zora Latinovic, ''Krvna Osveta'', 2005</ref>\n\nThe practice started in [[the Balkans]] in the 15th century, under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule and the law decreased in the 19th century, when the Balkan countries slowly got their independence from the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=\"glas-javnosti\">{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2005/07/29/srpski/F05072802.shtml |title=glas-javnosti |publisher=arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs|accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref> In pre-Ottoman [[Serbian lands|Serbian principalities]], [[blood money (term)|blood money]] (''Vra\u017eda'') was paid, one half went to the Serbian Orthodox Church, while the other to the victim's family. Stefan Uro\u0161 (1240\u20131272) talks about the Vra\u017eda in his works. After Ottoman conquest of [[Serbia]], self-governing clans often feuded with each other. Families in Serbia abandoned the tradition as the bigger threats to family integrity was ethnic Albanians and Turks rather than of their own ethnic group.\n\nWhen a family member has been killed, the perpetrator's family (brotherhoods/clans ''Bratstva'') has a \"Blood debt\" (''krvni dug'') which can only be removed when the victim's family (an appointed member, ''osvetnik'') has had their revenge by killing the aggressor or any member of the murderer's family (Often a close male kinsman, preferably the brother, killing of children was not encouraged). Only then has the family of the victim received peace (However, the blood feud continues if a relative decides to revenge, regardless of who started).<ref name=\"BF\" /> However, killing in your own house is the worst action, representing unmorality, which is a great shame in Montenegrin culture. If a criminal was murdered, it often did not result in a feud as criminality was negative in the eyes of society, but in some cases the criminal's family went on to kill serdars and other high ranked people.\n\n*In Montenegro, among local Slavic peoples the feuds predominantly affected [[Montenegrins]].\n*In Herzegovina (currently a region of both Montenegro and [[Bosnia & Herzegovina]]) [[Montenegrins]] had feuds with each other. A neutral region was Grahovo and Vu\u010dja Zuba (triangle of [[Boka Kotorska]], [[Montenegro]] and Herzegovina) where blood feuds were not recorded.\n*In [[Kosovo]]{{ref label|status|a|}} and [[North Macedonia|northern Macedonia]], if a Serb had a weak family, he could be protected by an Albanian clan from other [[Albanians]] in exchange for anything from [[weapons]] or [[folk attire]] [[textile|material]] (Serbs had rich textile art in the southern regions)\n\nThe Osveta is not limited to males, females that have their husbands or relatives killed could take on the ''blood debt'', an instance is recorded from the [[Bjelopavli\u0107i (clan)|Bjelopavli\u0107i clan]], where a widow took out revenge for the murder of her husband.<ref name=\"BF\">{{Google books |id=oq4B2WGT9mYC |title=Blood Revenge: The Enactment and Management of Conflict in Montenegro and Other Tribal Societies }}</ref>\n\nIf a bratstva finds and captures a thief or murderer (in connection to the bratstva) they could go to the person's house or relatives and tell them that their relative is a murderer or thief and end with something like \"If we kill him, we are not to be held for\" If the relatives answers \"Do what you like with him\" -the bratstva, if they kill the captive, they don't have a blood debt to his relatives because they settled his fate.\n\nThe blood feuds resulted in major instability in Montenegro, Kosovo and diaspora of Montenegrins in later centuries. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gjakmarrja]] - the equivalent cultural practice among Albanians.\n\n==Notes==\n{| style=\"margin-left:13px; line-height:150%\"\n|align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"|a.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|{{note|status}}{{Kosovo-note}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Crime in Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Feuds]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin culture]]\n[[Category:History of Montenegro]]\n\n[[sr:\u041a\u0440\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the album by Dvorska Luda|Krvna osveta (album)}}\n{{redirect|Zakletva|the album by Stoja|Zakletva (album)}}\n'''Krvna Osveta''' ({{lang-sr|\u041a\u0440\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430}}, '''''[[Blood feud]]''''') is a [[law]] of [[Feud|vendetta]] among South Slavic peoples in [[Montenegro]] and [[Herzegovina]], practised by [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]] and [[Bosniaks]] throughout history since medieval times. It is an oath of revenge for vendetta, meaning that the person must take revenge on whomever killed his relative by killing the murderer or one of the murderer's close relatives.<ref>Zora Latinovic, ''Krvna Osveta'', 2005</ref>\n\nThe practice started in [[the Balkans]] in the 15th century, under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule and the law decreased in the 19th century, when the Balkan countries slowly got their independence from the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=\"glas-javnosti\">{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2005/07/29/srpski/F05072802.shtml |title=glas-javnosti |publisher=arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs|accessdate=2015-08-27}}</ref> In pre-Ottoman [[Serbian lands|Serbian principalities]], [[blood money (term)|blood money]] (''Vra\u017eda'') was paid, one half went to the Serbian Orthodox Church, while the other to the victim's family. Stefan Uro\u0161 (1240\u20131272) talks about the Vra\u017eda in his works. After Ottoman conquest of [[Serbia]], self-governing clans often feuded with each other. Families in Serbia abandoned the tradition as the bigger threats to family integrity was ethnic Albanians and Turks rather than of their own ethnic group.\n\nWhen a family member has been killed, the perpetrator's family (brotherhoods/clans ''Bratstva'') has a \"Blood debt\" (''krvni dug'') which can only be removed when the victim's family (an appointed member, ''osvetnik'') has had their revenge by killing the aggressor or any member of the murderer's family (Often a close male kinsman, preferably the brother, killing of children was not encouraged). Only then has the family of the victim received peace (However, the blood feud continues if a relative decides to revenge, irregardless of who started).<ref name=\"BF\" /> However, killing in your own house is the worst action, representing unmorality, which is a great shame in Montenegrin culture. If a criminal was murdered, it often did not result in a feud as criminality was negative in the eyes of society, but in some cases the criminal's family went on to kill serdars and other high ranked people.\n\n*In Montenegro, among local Slavic peoples the feuds predominantly affected [[Montenegrins]].\n*In Herzegovina (currently a region of both Montenegro and [[Bosnia & Herzegovina]]) [[Montenegrins]] had feuds with each other. A neutral region was Grahovo and Vu\u010dja Zuba (triangle of [[Boka Kotorska]], [[Montenegro]] and Herzegovina) where blood feuds were not recorded.\n*In [[Kosovo]]{{ref label|status|a|}} and [[North Macedonia|northern Macedonia]], if a Serb had a weak family, he could be protected by an Albanian clan from other [[Albanians]] in exchange for anything from [[weapons]] or [[folk attire]] [[textile|material]] (Serbs had rich textile art in the southern regions)\n\nThe Osveta is not limited to males, females that have their husbands or relatives killed could take on the ''blood debt'', an instance is recorded from the [[Bjelopavli\u0107i (clan)|Bjelopavli\u0107i clan]], where a widow took out revenge for the murder of her husband.<ref name=\"BF\">{{Google books |id=oq4B2WGT9mYC |title=Blood Revenge: The Enactment and Management of Conflict in Montenegro and Other Tribal Societies }}</ref>\n\nIf a bratstva finds and captures a thief or murderer (in connection to the bratstva) they could go to the person's house or relatives and tell them that their relative is a murderer or thief and end with something like \"If we kill him, we are not to be held for\" If the relatives answers \"Do what you like with him\" -the bratstva, if they kill the captive, they don't have a blood debt to his relatives because they settled his fate.\n\nThe blood feuds resulted in major instability in Montenegro, Kosovo and diaspora of Montenegrins in later centuries. \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gjakmarrja]] - the equivalent cultural practice among Albanians.\n\n==Notes==\n{| style=\"margin-left:13px; line-height:150%\"\n|align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"|a.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n|{{note|status}}{{Kosovo-note}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Crime in Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Feuds]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin culture]]\n[[Category:History of Montenegro]]\n\n[[sr:\u041a\u0440\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430]]\n", "name_user": "JackofOz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krvna_osveta"}
{"title_page": "Martinique/Transportation", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Martinique]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Martinique]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Martinique/Transportation&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "OPV AIDS conspiracy theory", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Main|AIDS origin|Discredited HIV/AIDS origins theories}}\n{{Alternative medicine sidebar |conspiracy}}\nThe '''oral polio vaccine (OPV) AIDS theory''' posits that the [[AIDS]] [[pandemic]] originated from live [[polio vaccine]]s prepared in [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]] tissue cultures and then administered to up to one million Africans between 1957 and 1960 in experimental mass vaccination campaigns.\n\nData analyses in [[molecular biology]] and [[phylogenetic]] studies contradict the OPV AIDS hypothesis; consequently, [[scientific consensus]] regards the hypothesis as disproven.<ref name=Science>{{cite journal |author=Hillis DM |title=AIDS. Origins of HIV |journal=Science |volume=288 |issue=5472 |pages=1757\u20131759 |year=2000 |pmid=10877695 |doi=10.1126/science.288.5472.1757}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Birmingham K |title=Results make a monkey of OPV-AIDS theory |journal=Nat Med |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=1067 |year=2000 |pmid=11017114 |doi=10.1038/80356}}</ref><ref name=\"cohen2\"/><ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/iso/concerns/archive/aids_and_vaccines.htm Origin of Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV/AIDS)] [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] website, Accessed 30 January 2007</ref> The journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' has described the hypothesis as \"refuted\".<ref name=\"worobey\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Worobey M, Santiago M, Keele B, Ndjango J, Joy J, Labama B, Dhed'A B, Rambaut A, Sharp P, Shaw G, Hahn B |title=Origin of AIDS: contaminated polio vaccine theory refuted |journal=Nature |volume=428 |issue=6985 |pages=820 |year=2004 |pmid=15103367 |doi=10.1038/428820a}}</ref>\n\n== Background: polio vaccines ==\n{{details|Polio vaccine}}\nTwo [[vaccine]]s are used throughout the world to combat [[poliomyelitis]].  The first polio vaccine, developed by [[Jonas Salk]], is an ''inactivated [[poliovirus]] vaccine'' (IPV), consisting of a mixture of three wild, [[virulent]] strains of poliovirus, grown in a type of monkey [[kidney]] tissue culture ([[Vero cell]] line), and made noninfectious by [[formalin]] treatment. The second vaccine, an ''oral polio vaccine'' (OPV), is a live-[[attenuated vaccine]], produced by the passage of the virus through non-human cells at a sub-[[physiological]] temperature. The passage of virus produces mutations within the viral genome, and hinders the virus's ability to infect nervous tissue.<ref name=Kew_2005>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kew O, Sutter R, de Gourville E, Dowdle W, Pallansch M |title=Vaccine-derived polioviruses and the endgame strategy for global polio eradication |journal=Annu Rev Microbiol |volume=59 |issue=1 |pages=587\u2013635 |year=2005 |pmid=16153180 |doi=10.1146/annurev.micro.58.030603.123625|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1235033 }}</ref>\n\nBoth vaccines have been used for decades to induce [[immunity (medical)|immunity]] to polio, and to stop the spread of the infection. However, OPV has several advantages; because the vaccine is introduced in the gastrointestinal tract, the primary site of poliovirus infection and replication, it closely mimics a natural infection. OPV also provides long lasting immunity, and stimulates the production of polio neutralizing [[antibody|antibodies]] in the [[pharynx]] and gut.<ref name = Pearce>{{cite journal |author=Pearce J |title=Salk and Sabin: poliomyelitis immunisation |url= http://jnnp.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/75/11/1552 |journal=J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry |volume=75 |issue=11 |pages=1552 |year=2004 |pmid = 15489385 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.2003.028530 |pmc=1738787}}</ref> Hence, OPV not only prevents paralytic poliomyelitis, but also, when given in sufficient doses, can stop a threatening epidemic. Other benefits of OPV include ease of administration, low cost and suitability for mass vaccination campaigns.<ref name=Kew_2005/>\n\n=== Oral polio vaccine ===\nOral polio vaccines were developed in the late 1950s by several groups, including those led by [[Albert Sabin]], [[Hilary Koprowski]] and [[H. R. Cox]].<ref name=Furesz>{{cite journal |author=Furesz J |title=Developments in the production and quality control of poliovirus vaccines \u2013 Historical perspectives |journal=Biologicals |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=87\u201390 |year=2006 |pmid=16621594 |doi=10.1016/j.biologicals.2006.02.008}}</ref> A poliovirus type 1 strain called SM was reported in 1954. A less virulent version of the SM strain was reported by Koprowski in 1957. The name of the vaccine strain was \"CHAT\" after \"Charlton\", the name of the child who was the donor of the precursor virus.<ref name=Plotkin>{{cite journal |author=Plotkin SA |last2=Modlin |first2=J. F. |last3=Plotkin |first3=S. A. |title=CHAT oral polio vaccine was not the source of human immunodeficiency virus type 1 group M for humans|journal=Clin. Infect. Dis. |volume=32 |issue=7 |pages=1068\u20131084 |year=2001 |pmid=11264036 |doi=10.1086/319612}}</ref> The Sabin, Koprowski and Cox vaccines were clinically tested in millions of individuals and found to be safe and effective. Because monkey trials found fewer side effects with the Sabin vaccine, in the early 1960s, the Sabin vaccine was licensed in the USA and its use supported by the World Health Organization.<ref name=\"Furesz\"/>\n\nBetween 1957 and 1960, Koprowski's vaccine was administered to roughly one million people in the Belgian territories, now the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Rwanda]] and [[Burundi]].<ref name=Plotkin/> In 1960, Koprowski wrote in the ''British Medical Journal'', \"The Belgian Congo trials have enlarged considerably and ... more vaccination campaigns organized in several provinces of the Belgian Congo are raising the number of vaccinated individuals into the millions.\"''(p.&nbsp;90)'' Koprowski and his group also published a series of detailed reports on the vaccination of 76,000 children under the age of 5 (and European adults) in the area of Leopoldville (now [[Kinshasa]]) in Belgian Congo from 1958\u20131960; these reports begin with an overview,<ref name=Koprowski5>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.2.5192.85 |author=Koprowski H |title=Historical aspects of the development of live virus vaccine in poliomyelitis |journal=Br Med J |volume=2 |issue=5192 |pages=85\u201391 |date=July 1960 |pmid=14410975 |pmc=2096806 }}</ref> next a review of safety and efficacy,<ref name=Koproski2>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, LeBrun A, Koprowski H |title=Vaccination with the CHAT strain of type 1 attenuated poliomyelitis virus in Leopoldville. Belgian Congo 2. Studies of the safety and efficacy of vaccination |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=22 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=215\u201334 |year=1960 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1960/Vol22/Vol22-No3-4/bulletin_1960_22(3-4)_215-234.pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206221524/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1960/Vol22/Vol22-No3-4/bulletin_1960_22(3-4)_215-234.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all |pmid=14433516 }}</ref> then a 21-month follow-up and final report.<ref name=Koproski3>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, LeBrun A, Courtois G, Koprowski H |title=Vaccination with the CHAT strain of type 1 attenuated poliomyelitis virus in Leopoldville, Congo 3. Safety and efficacy during the first 21 months of study |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=24 |issue=6 |pages=785\u201392 |year=1961 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1961/Vol24/Vol24-No6/bulletin_1961_24(6)_785-792.pdf |pmid=13736381 |pmc=2555526 |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206221712/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1961/Vol24/Vol24-No6/bulletin_1961_24(6)_785-792.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vaccine production ===\nIn the 1950s, before dangers inherent to the process were well controlled, seed stocks of vaccines were occasionally transported to distant regions, then standard [[tissue culture]] methods<ref name=Enders>{{cite book |author=Enders, John |chapter=The present status of tissue-culture techniques in the study of poliomyelitis viruses |editor=Debr\u00e9, R. |title=Poliomyelitis |publisher=World Health Organization |location=Geneva |year=1955 |pages=269\u201394 |chapter-url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222216/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Rappaport>{{cite journal |author=Rappaport, Catherine |title=Trypsinization of Monkey-Kidney Tissue: Automatic Method for the Preparation of Cell Suspensions |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=147\u201366 |year=1956 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1956/Vol14/Vol14-No1/bulletin_1956_14(1)_147-166.pdf |pmid=13329843 |pmc=2538109 |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222137/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1956/Vol14/Vol14-No1/bulletin_1956_14(1)_147-166.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Melnick>Melnick, JL (1956) \"Tissue culture methods for the cultivation of poliomyelitis and other viruses\", in American Public Health Association, ''Diagnostic Procedures for Virus and Rickettsial Diseases'' 2nd ed., New York, pp. 97\u2013151</ref> were used to amplify the virus at local production facilities. Biologic products, chiefly kidney cells for cultures and blood serum for media, were sometimes harvested from local primates and used in the production process if wild or captive populations of appropriate species were available.<ref name=Rhodes>{{cite book |vauthors=Rhodes AJ, Wood W, Duncan D |chapter=The present place of virus laboratory tests in the diagnosis of poliomyelitis, with special reference to tissue-culture techniques |editor=Debr\u00e9, R. |title=Poliomyelitis |publisher=World Health Organization |location=Geneva |year=1955 |chapter-url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222216/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}237\u201367</ref> In [[South Africa]], [[African green monkey]] tissue was used to amplify the Sabin vaccine. In [[French West Africa]] and [[Equatorial Africa]], [[baboons]] were used to amplify a vaccine from the Pasteur Institute. In Poland, the CHAT vaccine was amplified using Asian [[macaques]].<ref name=PlotkinSA/>\n\n== Development of hypothesis ==\nIn 1987, Blaine Elswood contacted journalist Tom Curtis about a \"bombshell story\" on OPV and AIDS. Curtis published an article on the OPV AIDS hypothesis in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |author=Curtis, Tom |authorlink=Tom Curtis (journalist) |title=The Origin of AIDS: A startling new theory attempts to answer the question, 'Was it an act of God or an act of man? |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=626 |pages=54\u20139, 61, 106, 108 |date=19 March 1992 }}</ref> In response, Hilary Koprowski sued ''Rolling Stone'' and Tom Curtis for [[defamation]]. The magazine published a clarification which praised Koprowski and stated:\n{{Quotation|The editors of Rolling Stone wish to clarify that they never intended to suggest in the article that there is any scientific proof, nor do they know of any scientific proof, that Dr. Koprowski, an illustrious scientist, was in fact responsible for introducing AIDS to the human population or that he is the father of AIDS.<ref name=RS671>{{cite news |author=Editor |title='Origin of AIDS' update - Clarification |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=671 |page=39 |date=December 9, 1993 }} This 'Clarification' article forms part of the defamation settlement when Hilary Koprowski sued Tom Curtis & Rolling Stone magazine in 1992-93.</ref>}} ''Rolling Stone'' was ordered to pay $1 [[USD]] in damages whilst incurring around $500,000 USD in legal fees for its own defense.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Martin B |title=Investigating the origin of AIDS: some ethical dimensions |journal=J Med Ethics |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=253\u2013256 |date=August 2003 |pmid=12930866 |pmc=1733782 |doi=10.1136/jme.29.4.253 |url=http://jme.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/29/4/253}}</ref>\n\nA few scientists, notably the biologist [[W. D. Hamilton]], thought the hypothesis required serious investigation, but they received little support from the scientific community.\n\nJournalist Edward Hooper detailed the hypothesis in his 1999 book, ''The River''. Hooper further expanded on his allegations in a 2000 meeting in London, at the [[Royal Society]], although these claims were later rebutted by some of the scientists who were present at the meeting.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, Teuwen DE, Prinzie A, Desmyter J |title=Postscript relating to new allegations made by Edward Hooper at The Royal Society Discussion Meeting on 11 September 2000 |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=825\u2013829 |year=2001 |pmid=11405926 |url=http://journals.royalsociety.org/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0962-8436&volume=356&issue=1410&spage=825 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0875 |pmc=1088472}}</ref> In 2001, Hilary Koprowski responded by making a detailed rebuttal of the points made in the book, also in a talk to the Royal Society.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Koprowski H |title=Hypotheses and facts |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=831\u2013833 |year=2001 |pmid=11405927 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0869 |pmc=1088473}}</ref> In 2004, the ''Origin of Aids'', a French TV documentary strongly supportive of the OPV hypothesis, appeared on several television stations around the world.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0438938/ | title=Les origines du SIDA}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cg-map.png|275px|thumb|right|The Laboratoire M\u00e9dical de Stanleyville was sited at the city now known as [[Kisangani]]]]\n\nIn 2003, Hooper published additional statements that he believed supported his hypothesis in an article in the ''[[London Review of Books]]''. These included accounts of an interview with Jacques Kanyama, a virology technician at the lab in Stanleyville (the Laboratoire M\u00e9dical de Stanleyville (LMS)) responsible for testing the CHAT vaccine and performing the initial set of vaccinations, who was reported to have said that batches of CHAT had been produced on site by Paul Osterrieth. In addition, Philip Elebe, a microbiology technician, was claimed to have said that tissue cultures were being produced from Lindi chimpanzees. Osterrieth has denied these claims and stated that this work would not have been possible in this laboratory,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Osterrieth PM |authorlink=Paul Osterrieth |title=Vaccine could not have been prepared in Stanleyville |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=839 |date=June 2001 |pmid=11405929 |pmc=1088475 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0872 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Osterrieth P |authorlink=Paul Osterrieth |title=Oral polio vaccine: fact versus fiction |journal=Vaccine |volume=22 |issue=15\u201316 |pages=1831\u20131835 |date=May 2004 |pmid=15121291 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2004.01.028 }}</ref><ref name=PlotkinSA/> stating that:\n\n{{Quotation|at no time did I ever attempt to make cell cultures from chimpanzee tissues. In addition, I wish to state categorically that no poliovaccine was ever produced or could have been produced in Stanleyville, since the facilities were totally inadequate for the production or control of poliovaccine.<ref name=PlotkinSA/>}}\n\nIn his book, Hooper also stated that Gaston Ninane was involved in using chimpanzee cells to produce vaccine in Congo. Ninane responded to this allegation by stating that he could \"categorically deny\" ever having tried to make tissue cultures from chimpanzee cells.<ref name=Plotkin/> The people involved in vaccine production and distribution from America state that no vaccine was prepared locally in Congo and that only the CHAT vaccine from America was used. Barbara Cohen, the technician who was responsible for running the American laboratory that produced this vaccine stated:\n\n{{Quotation|At no time did I ever receive or work on chimpanzee kidneys, nor to my knowledge cells derived from chimpanzees. I never made, nor do I know of anyone in the lab who made polio vaccine in chimpanzee cells.<ref name=PlotkinSA>{{cite journal |author=Plotkin SA |title=Untruths and consequences: the false hypothesis linking CHAT type 1 polio vaccination to the origin of human immunodeficiency virus |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=815\u2013823 |year=2001 |pmid=11405925 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0861 |pmc=1088471}}</ref>}}\n\n== Scientific investigation ==\nThe OPV AIDS hypothesis has been examined and rejected by the scientific and medical communities as being unsupported or directly contradicted by available data, and inconsistent with HIV [[epidemiology]].\n\nIn an August 1992 letter published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', Koprowski repudiated the OPV AIDS hypothesis, pointing to multiple errors of fact in its assertions.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Koprowski |title=AIDS and the Polio Vaccine |journal=Science |volume=257 |issue=5073 |pages=1024\u20131027 |year=1992 |doi=10.1126/science.257.5073.1024 |pmid=1509249}}</ref> In October 1992, ''Science'' ran a story titled \"Panel Nixes Congo Vaccine as AIDS source,\" describing the findings of an independent panel which found each proposed step in the OPV-AIDS hypothesis \"problematic\". The story concluded:\n{{Quotation|...it can be stated with almost complete certainty that the large polio vaccine trial... was not the origin of AIDS.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panel nixes Congo trials as AIDS source |journal=Science |volume=258 |issue=5083 |pages=738\u20139 |year=1992 |pmid=1439779 | doi=10.1126/science.258.5083.738-d  }}</ref>}}\n\nThe oldest confirmed sample of human tissue that shows the presence of HIV-1 is an archival sample of plasma collected from an anonymous donor in the city of Leopoldville, Belgian Congo (now [[Kinshasa]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]) in 1959 and was found with retrospective genetic analysis to be most closely related to subtype D strains. In 2008, partial HIV viral sequences were identified from a specimen of lymph node collected from an adult female, also in Kinshasa, in 1960. This specimen, named DRC60, was around 88% similar to ZR59, but was found to be most closely related to subtype A HIV-1 strains. These specimens are significant not only because they are the oldest specimens of the virus known to cause AIDS, but because they show that the virus already had an extensive amount of genetic diversity in 1960.<ref>Worobey M, Gemmel M, Teuwen DE, Haselkorn T, Kunstman K, Bunce M, Muyembe JJ, Kabongo JM, Kalengayi RM, Van Marck E, Gilbert MT, Wolinsky SM. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18833279 Direct evidence of extensive diversity of HIV-1 in Kinshasa by 1960.] Nature. 2008 Oct 2;455(7213):661-4.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the [[Royal Society]] held a meeting to discuss data on the [[AIDS origin|origin of AIDS]]; the OPV AIDS hypothesis was a central topic of discussion. At this meeting, three independent labs released the results of tests on the remaining stocks of Koprowski's vaccine, which Edward Hooper had demanded in ''The River''. The tests confirmed Koprowski's contention that his vaccine was made from monkey, rather than chimpanzee, kidney, and found no evidence of SIV or HIV contamination. Additional epidemiologic and phylogenetic data was presented at the conference which undermined other aspects of the OPV AIDS hypothesis. According to a report in ''Science'',<ref name=\"cohen0\">{{cite web |url= http://news.sciencemag.org/2000/09/vaccine-theory-aids-takes-blow|title= Vaccine Theory of AIDS Takes a Blow|last1= Cohen|first1= Jon|date= 12 September 2000|website= Science|access-date= November 2015}}</ref> Hooper \"did not challenge the results; he simply dismissed them.\"\n\nIn 2001, three articles published in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' examined various aspects of the OPV-AIDS hypothesis, as did an article published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]''. In every case, the studies' findings argued strongly against any link between the polio vaccine and AIDS.<ref name=\"blancou\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Blancou P, Vartanian J, Christopherson C, Chenciner N, Basilico C, Kwok S, Wain-Hobson S |title=Polio vaccine samples not linked to AIDS |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1045\u20131046 |year=2001 |pmid=11323657 |doi=10.1038/35074171}}</ref><ref name=\"berry\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Berry N, Davis C, Jenkins A, Wood D, Minor P, Schild G, Bottiger M, Holmes H, Almond N |title=Vaccine safety. Analysis of oral polio vaccine CHAT stocks |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1046\u20131047 |year=2001 |pmid=11323658 |doi=10.1038/35074176}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rambaut A, Robertson DL, Pybus OG, Peeters M, Holmes EC |title=Human immunodeficiency virus. Phylogeny and the origin of HIV-1 |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1047\u20131048 |year=2001 |pmid=11323659 |doi=10.1038/35074179}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Poinar H, Kuch M, P\u00e4\u00e4bo S |title=Molecular analyses of oral polio vaccine samples |journal=Science |volume=292 |issue=5517 |pages=743\u2013744 |year=2001 |pmid=11326104 |doi=10.1126/science.1058463|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ceae60b70620c6dd9d1089e129d4f17051423b66 }}</ref> The evidence cited included multiple independent studies that dated the introduction of HIV-1 to humans as occurring between 1915 and 1941, probably in the 1930s.<ref name=Korber>{{cite journal |author=Korber B |title=Timing the ancestor of the HIV-1 pandemic strains |journal=Science |volume=288 |issue=5472 |pages=1789\u201396 |year=2000 |pmid=10846155 |doi=10.1126/science.288.5472.1789 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Muldoon M |author3=Theiler J |display-authors=3 |last4=Gao |first4=F |last5=Gupta |first5=R |last6=Lapedes |first6=A |last7=Hahn |first7=BH |last8=Wolinsky |first8=S |last9=Bhattacharya |first9=T|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1231201 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Salemi M |title=Dating the common ancestor of SIVcpz and HIV-1 group M and the origin of HIV-1 subtypes using a new method to uncover clock-like molecular evolution |journal=FASEB J. |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=276\u20138 |year=2001 |pmid=11156935 |doi=10.1096/fj.00-0449fje |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Strimmer K |author3=Hall WW |display-authors=3 |last4=Duffy |first4=M |last5=Delaporte |first5=E |last6=Mboup |first6=S |last7=Peeters |first7=M |last8=Vandamme |first8=AM}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sharp PM, Bailes E, Chaudhuri RR, Rodenburg CM, Santiago MO, Hahn BH |title=The origins of acquired immune deficiency syndrome viruses: where and when? |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=867\u2013876 |year=2001 |pmid=11405934 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0863 |url=http://journals.royalsociety.org/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0962-8436&volume=356&issue=1410&spage=867 |pmc=1088480 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These results were confirmed by a later study using samples from the 1960s that also found that the epidemic began between 1908 and 1930,<ref name=Worobey2008>{{cite journal |author=Worobey M |title=Direct evidence of extensive diversity of HIV-1 in Kinshasa by 1960 |journal=Nature |volume=455 |issue=7213 |pages=661\u20134 |date=October 2008 |pmid=18833279 |doi=10.1038/nature07390 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Gemmel M |author3=Teuwen DE |display-authors=3 |last4=Haselkorn |first4=Tamara |last5=Kunstman |first5=Kevin |last6=Bunce |first6=Michael |last7=Muyembe |first7=Jean-Jacques |last8=Kabongo |first8=Jean-Marie M. |last9=Kalengayi |first9=Rapha\u00ebl M. |pmc=3682493}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web |url=http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnJOE491050.html |title=News Africa |work=Reuters.com |accessdate=2008-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005034208/http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnJOE491050.html |archivedate=5 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and a study that showed that although recombination amongst viruses makes dating less precise, it does not significantly bias estimates in either direction (it does not introduce a [[systematic error]]).<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lemey P |title=The molecular population genetics of HIV-1 group O |journal=Genetics |volume=167 |issue=3 |pages=1059\u201368 |date=July 2004 |pmid=15280223 |pmc=1470933 |doi=10.1534/genetics.104.026666 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Pybus OG |author3=Rambaut A |display-authors=3 |last4=Drummond |first4=AJ |last5=Robertson |first5=DL |last6=Roques |first6=P |last7=Worobey |first7=M |last8=Vandamme |first8=AM }}</ref>\n\nThe author of one of the studies, [[evolutionary biologist]] Edward Holmes of [[Oxford University]], commented in light of the new evidence: \"Hooper's evidence was always flimsy, and now it's untenable. It's time to move on.\"<ref name=\"cohen2\">{{cite journal |author=Cohen J |title=AIDS origins. Disputed AIDS theory dies its final death |journal=Science |volume=292 |issue=5517 |pages=615a\u2013615 |year=2001 |pmid=11330303 |doi=10.1126/science.292.5517.615a}}</ref> An accompanying editorial in ''Nature'' concluded:\n{{Quotation|The new data may not convince the hardened conspiracy theorist who thinks that contamination of OPV by chimpanzee virus was subsequently and deliberately covered up. But those of us who were formerly willing to give some credence to the OPV hypothesis will now consider that the matter has been laid to rest.<ref name=Weiss>{{cite journal |author=Weiss RA |title=Polio vaccines exonerated |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1035\u20131036 |year=2001 |pmid=11323649 |doi=10.1038/35074222}}</ref>}}\n\nThe possibility that chimpanzees found near Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of Congo (formerly Stanleyville) were, indirectly, the true source of HIV-1 was directly addressed in a 2004 study published in ''Nature''. Here, the authors found that while SIV was present in chimpanzees in the area, the strain of SIV infecting these chimpanzees was [[phylogeny|phylogenetically]] distinct from all strains of HIV, providing direct evidence that these particular chimps were not the source of HIV in humans.<ref name=\"worobey\"/>\n\n== Current oral polio-vaccine campaign in Africa ==\nRumours that polio vaccines are unsafe disrupted the longstanding effort of the [[WHO]] and [[UN]] to achieve [[poliomyelitis eradication]] worldwide through use of the oral polio vaccine of [[Albert Sabin]], which is thought to be safe and effective by virtually all medical authorities. If this long-term public-health goal could be achieved, [[poliomyelitis]] would follow [[smallpox]] as the second eradicated infectious human disease. The OPV AIDS hypothesis relates only to the historical origin of AIDS, and its proponents have accepted the safety of the modern polio vaccines, but rumors based on a misunderstanding of the hypothesis exist,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2070634.stm Nigeria Muslims oppose polio vaccination] ''BBC News'' 27 June 2002</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/20/international/asia/20polio.html?pagewanted=2 Rumor, Fear and Fatigue Hinder Final Push to End Polio] Celia W. Dugger and Donald G. McNeil Jr. ''New York Times'' 20 March 2006</ref> and those rumors are blamed in part for the recent failure to eliminate polio in [[Nigeria]].<ref name=Jegede>{{cite journal |author=Jegede AS |title=What led to the Nigerian boycott of the polio vaccination campaign? |journal=PLOS Med. |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=e73 |year=2007 |pmid=17388657 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.0040073 |pmc=1831725}}</ref>\n\nBy 2003, cases of poliomyelitis had been reduced to just a small number in isolated regions of [[West Africa]], with sporadic cases elsewhere.  However, the disease has since resurged in Nigeria and in several other nations of Africa, which epidemiologists trace to refusals by certain local populations to allow their children to be administered the Sabin oral vaccine. The expressed concerns of local populations often relate to fears that the vaccine might induce sterility,<ref name=BBC>BBC News (2005) \"Anti-polio vaccine Malians jailed\" [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4539757.stm online]</ref> and it seems that debate over the OPV-AIDS hypothesis has fueled additional fears.<ref name=Hooper1>Cohen, Jon (2000) ''[[Atlantic Monthly]]'' (Oct), p. 104.</ref> Since 2003, these fears have spread among some in the Muslim community, with Datti Ahmed, of the Supreme Council for Sharia in Nigeria stating that:\n\n{{quotation|\u201cWe believe that modern-day Hitlers have deliberately adulterated the oral polio vaccines with anti-fertility drugs and viruses which are known to cause HIV and AIDS.\u201d<ref name=Jegede/>}}\n\nPolio has also resurged in areas of Pakistan, India and Bangladesh.<ref name=GPEI>[[Global Polio Eradication Initiative]] (2007) Map of last six months of polio cases worldwide ''Wild Poliovirus Weekly Update'' initiative of WHO, CDC, UNICEF, Rotary International [http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casemap.shtml online] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20060925135122/http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casemap.shtml |date=25 September 2006 }}</ref><ref name=BBC2>BBC News (2007) \"Bangladesh begins new polio drive\" [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6412835.stm online]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[AIDS origins opposed to scientific consensus]]\n*[[AIDS origin]]\n*[[SV40]] A scientifically accepted case of a monkey virus contaminating polio vaccine \u2013 Inactivated poliovirus vaccine (IPV) only.\n*[[Zoonosis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181743/http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/resources/qa/qa3.htm Where did HIV come from? Questions and Answers], from the United States [[Centers for Disease Control]]\n\n{{AIDS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Opv Aids Hypothesis}}\n[[Category:AIDS origin hypotheses]]\n[[Category:Vaccine controversies]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n\n[[fr:Origine du virus de l'immunod\u00e9ficience humaine#La th\u00e9orie du vaccin anti-polio (en cours d'\u00e9laboration)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Main|AIDS origin|Discredited HIV/AIDS origins theories}}\n{{Alternative medicine sidebar |conspiracy}}\nThe '''oral polio vaccine (OPV) AIDS conspiracy theory''' posits that the [[AIDS]] [[pandemic]] originated from live [[polio vaccine]]s prepared in [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzee]] tissue cultures and then administered to up to one million Africans between 1957 and 1960 in experimental mass vaccination campaigns.\n\nData analyses in [[molecular biology]] and [[phylogenetic]] studies contradict the OPV AIDS hypothesis; consequently, [[scientific consensus]] regards the hypothesis as disproven.<ref name=Science>{{cite journal |author=Hillis DM |title=AIDS. Origins of HIV |journal=Science |volume=288 |issue=5472 |pages=1757\u20131759 |year=2000 |pmid=10877695 |doi=10.1126/science.288.5472.1757}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Birmingham K |title=Results make a monkey of OPV-AIDS theory |journal=Nat Med |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=1067 |year=2000 |pmid=11017114 |doi=10.1038/80356}}</ref><ref name=\"cohen2\"/><ref>[https://www.cdc.gov/od/science/iso/concerns/archive/aids_and_vaccines.htm Origin of Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV/AIDS)] [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] website, Accessed 30 January 2007</ref> The journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' has described the hypothesis as \"refuted\".<ref name=\"worobey\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Worobey M, Santiago M, Keele B, Ndjango J, Joy J, Labama B, Dhed'A B, Rambaut A, Sharp P, Shaw G, Hahn B |title=Origin of AIDS: contaminated polio vaccine theory refuted |journal=Nature |volume=428 |issue=6985 |pages=820 |year=2004 |pmid=15103367 |doi=10.1038/428820a}}</ref>\n\n== Background: polio vaccines ==\n{{details|Polio vaccine}}\nTwo [[vaccine]]s are used throughout the world to combat [[poliomyelitis]].  The first polio vaccine, developed by [[Jonas Salk]], is an ''inactivated [[poliovirus]] vaccine'' (IPV), consisting of a mixture of three wild, [[virulent]] strains of poliovirus, grown in a type of monkey [[kidney]] tissue culture ([[Vero cell]] line), and made noninfectious by [[formalin]] treatment. The second vaccine, an ''oral polio vaccine'' (OPV), is a live-[[attenuated vaccine]], produced by the passage of the virus through non-human cells at a sub-[[physiological]] temperature. The passage of virus produces mutations within the viral genome, and hinders the virus's ability to infect nervous tissue.<ref name=Kew_2005>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kew O, Sutter R, de Gourville E, Dowdle W, Pallansch M |title=Vaccine-derived polioviruses and the endgame strategy for global polio eradication |journal=Annu Rev Microbiol |volume=59 |issue=1 |pages=587\u2013635 |year=2005 |pmid=16153180 |doi=10.1146/annurev.micro.58.030603.123625|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1235033 }}</ref>\n\nBoth vaccines have been used for decades to induce [[immunity (medical)|immunity]] to polio, and to stop the spread of the infection. However, OPV has several advantages; because the vaccine is introduced in the gastrointestinal tract, the primary site of poliovirus infection and replication, it closely mimics a natural infection. OPV also provides long lasting immunity, and stimulates the production of polio neutralizing [[antibody|antibodies]] in the [[pharynx]] and gut.<ref name = Pearce>{{cite journal |author=Pearce J |title=Salk and Sabin: poliomyelitis immunisation |url= http://jnnp.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/75/11/1552 |journal=J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry |volume=75 |issue=11 |pages=1552 |year=2004 |pmid = 15489385 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.2003.028530 |pmc=1738787}}</ref> Hence, OPV not only prevents paralytic poliomyelitis, but also, when given in sufficient doses, can stop a threatening epidemic. Other benefits of OPV include ease of administration, low cost and suitability for mass vaccination campaigns.<ref name=Kew_2005/>\n\n=== Oral polio vaccine ===\nOral polio vaccines were developed in the late 1950s by several groups, including those led by [[Albert Sabin]], [[Hilary Koprowski]] and [[H. R. Cox]].<ref name=Furesz>{{cite journal |author=Furesz J |title=Developments in the production and quality control of poliovirus vaccines \u2013 Historical perspectives |journal=Biologicals |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=87\u201390 |year=2006 |pmid=16621594 |doi=10.1016/j.biologicals.2006.02.008}}</ref> A poliovirus type 1 strain called SM was reported in 1954. A less virulent version of the SM strain was reported by Koprowski in 1957. The name of the vaccine strain was \"CHAT\" after \"Charlton\", the name of the child who was the donor of the precursor virus.<ref name=Plotkin>{{cite journal |author=Plotkin SA |last2=Modlin |first2=J. F. |last3=Plotkin |first3=S. A. |title=CHAT oral polio vaccine was not the source of human immunodeficiency virus type 1 group M for humans|journal=Clin. Infect. Dis. |volume=32 |issue=7 |pages=1068\u20131084 |year=2001 |pmid=11264036 |doi=10.1086/319612}}</ref> The Sabin, Koprowski and Cox vaccines were clinically tested in millions of individuals and found to be safe and effective. Because monkey trials found fewer side effects with the Sabin vaccine, in the early 1960s, the Sabin vaccine was licensed in the USA and its use supported by the World Health Organization.<ref name=\"Furesz\"/>\n\nBetween 1957 and 1960, Koprowski's vaccine was administered to roughly one million people in the Belgian territories, now the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Rwanda]] and [[Burundi]].<ref name=Plotkin/> In 1960, Koprowski wrote in the ''British Medical Journal'', \"The Belgian Congo trials have enlarged considerably and ... more vaccination campaigns organized in several provinces of the Belgian Congo are raising the number of vaccinated individuals into the millions.\"''(p.&nbsp;90)'' Koprowski and his group also published a series of detailed reports on the vaccination of 76,000 children under the age of 5 (and European adults) in the area of Leopoldville (now [[Kinshasa]]) in Belgian Congo from 1958\u20131960; these reports begin with an overview,<ref name=Koprowski5>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.2.5192.85 |author=Koprowski H |title=Historical aspects of the development of live virus vaccine in poliomyelitis |journal=Br Med J |volume=2 |issue=5192 |pages=85\u201391 |date=July 1960 |pmid=14410975 |pmc=2096806 }}</ref> next a review of safety and efficacy,<ref name=Koproski2>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, LeBrun A, Koprowski H |title=Vaccination with the CHAT strain of type 1 attenuated poliomyelitis virus in Leopoldville. Belgian Congo 2. Studies of the safety and efficacy of vaccination |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=22 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=215\u201334 |year=1960 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1960/Vol22/Vol22-No3-4/bulletin_1960_22(3-4)_215-234.pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206221524/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1960/Vol22/Vol22-No3-4/bulletin_1960_22(3-4)_215-234.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all |pmid=14433516 }}</ref> then a 21-month follow-up and final report.<ref name=Koproski3>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, LeBrun A, Courtois G, Koprowski H |title=Vaccination with the CHAT strain of type 1 attenuated poliomyelitis virus in Leopoldville, Congo 3. Safety and efficacy during the first 21 months of study |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=24 |issue=6 |pages=785\u201392 |year=1961 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1961/Vol24/Vol24-No6/bulletin_1961_24(6)_785-792.pdf |pmid=13736381 |pmc=2555526 |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206221712/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1961/Vol24/Vol24-No6/bulletin_1961_24(6)_785-792.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Vaccine production ===\nIn the 1950s, before dangers inherent to the process were well controlled, seed stocks of vaccines were occasionally transported to distant regions, then standard [[tissue culture]] methods<ref name=Enders>{{cite book |author=Enders, John |chapter=The present status of tissue-culture techniques in the study of poliomyelitis viruses |editor=Debr\u00e9, R. |title=Poliomyelitis |publisher=World Health Organization |location=Geneva |year=1955 |pages=269\u201394 |chapter-url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222216/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Rappaport>{{cite journal |author=Rappaport, Catherine |title=Trypsinization of Monkey-Kidney Tissue: Automatic Method for the Preparation of Cell Suspensions |journal=Bull World Health Organ |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=147\u201366 |year=1956 |url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1956/Vol14/Vol14-No1/bulletin_1956_14(1)_147-166.pdf |pmid=13329843 |pmc=2538109 |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222137/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/bulletin/1956/Vol14/Vol14-No1/bulletin_1956_14(1)_147-166.pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Melnick>Melnick, JL (1956) \"Tissue culture methods for the cultivation of poliomyelitis and other viruses\", in American Public Health Association, ''Diagnostic Procedures for Virus and Rickettsial Diseases'' 2nd ed., New York, pp. 97\u2013151</ref> were used to amplify the virus at local production facilities. Biologic products, chiefly kidney cells for cultures and blood serum for media, were sometimes harvested from local primates and used in the production process if wild or captive populations of appropriate species were available.<ref name=Rhodes>{{cite book |vauthors=Rhodes AJ, Wood W, Duncan D |chapter=The present place of virus laboratory tests in the diagnosis of poliomyelitis, with special reference to tissue-culture techniques |editor=Debr\u00e9, R. |title=Poliomyelitis |publisher=World Health Organization |location=Geneva |year=1955 |chapter-url=http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |access-date=30 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206222216/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_26_(part3).pdf |archive-date=6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}237\u201367</ref> In [[South Africa]], [[African green monkey]] tissue was used to amplify the Sabin vaccine. In [[French West Africa]] and [[Equatorial Africa]], [[baboons]] were used to amplify a vaccine from the Pasteur Institute. In Poland, the CHAT vaccine was amplified using Asian [[macaques]].<ref name=PlotkinSA/>\n\n== Development of hypothesis ==\nIn 1987, Blaine Elswood contacted journalist Tom Curtis about a \"bombshell story\" on OPV and AIDS. Curtis published an article on the OPV AIDS hypothesis in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1992.<ref>{{cite news |author=Curtis, Tom |authorlink=Tom Curtis (journalist) |title=The Origin of AIDS: A startling new theory attempts to answer the question, 'Was it an act of God or an act of man? |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=626 |pages=54\u20139, 61, 106, 108 |date=19 March 1992 }}</ref> In response, Hilary Koprowski sued ''Rolling Stone'' and Tom Curtis for [[defamation]]. The magazine published a clarification which praised Koprowski and stated:\n{{Quotation|The editors of Rolling Stone wish to clarify that they never intended to suggest in the article that there is any scientific proof, nor do they know of any scientific proof, that Dr. Koprowski, an illustrious scientist, was in fact responsible for introducing AIDS to the human population or that he is the father of AIDS.<ref name=RS671>{{cite news |author=Editor |title='Origin of AIDS' update - Clarification |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=671 |page=39 |date=December 9, 1993 }} This 'Clarification' article forms part of the defamation settlement when Hilary Koprowski sued Tom Curtis & Rolling Stone magazine in 1992-93.</ref>}} ''Rolling Stone'' was ordered to pay $1 [[USD]] in damages whilst incurring around $500,000 USD in legal fees for its own defense.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Martin B |title=Investigating the origin of AIDS: some ethical dimensions |journal=J Med Ethics |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=253\u2013256 |date=August 2003 |pmid=12930866 |pmc=1733782 |doi=10.1136/jme.29.4.253 |url=http://jme.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/29/4/253}}</ref>\n\nA few scientists, notably the biologist [[W. D. Hamilton]], thought the hypothesis required serious investigation, but they received little support from the scientific community.\n\nJournalist Edward Hooper detailed the hypothesis in his 1999 book, ''The River''. Hooper further expanded on his allegations in a 2000 meeting in London, at the [[Royal Society]], although these claims were later rebutted by some of the scientists who were present at the meeting.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Plotkin SA, Teuwen DE, Prinzie A, Desmyter J |title=Postscript relating to new allegations made by Edward Hooper at The Royal Society Discussion Meeting on 11 September 2000 |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=825\u2013829 |year=2001 |pmid=11405926 |url=http://journals.royalsociety.org/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0962-8436&volume=356&issue=1410&spage=825 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0875 |pmc=1088472}}</ref> In 2001, Hilary Koprowski responded by making a detailed rebuttal of the points made in the book, also in a talk to the Royal Society.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Koprowski H |title=Hypotheses and facts |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=831\u2013833 |year=2001 |pmid=11405927 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0869 |pmc=1088473}}</ref> In 2004, the ''Origin of Aids'', a French TV documentary strongly supportive of the OPV hypothesis, appeared on several television stations around the world.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0438938/ | title=Les origines du SIDA}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cg-map.png|275px|thumb|right|The Laboratoire M\u00e9dical de Stanleyville was sited at the city now known as [[Kisangani]]]]\n\nIn 2003, Hooper published additional statements that he believed supported his hypothesis in an article in the ''[[London Review of Books]]''. These included accounts of an interview with Jacques Kanyama, a virology technician at the lab in Stanleyville (the Laboratoire M\u00e9dical de Stanleyville (LMS)) responsible for testing the CHAT vaccine and performing the initial set of vaccinations, who was reported to have said that batches of CHAT had been produced on site by Paul Osterrieth. In addition, Philip Elebe, a microbiology technician, was claimed to have said that tissue cultures were being produced from Lindi chimpanzees. Osterrieth has denied these claims and stated that this work would not have been possible in this laboratory,<ref>{{cite journal |author=Osterrieth PM |authorlink=Paul Osterrieth |title=Vaccine could not have been prepared in Stanleyville |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=839 |date=June 2001 |pmid=11405929 |pmc=1088475 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0872 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Osterrieth P |authorlink=Paul Osterrieth |title=Oral polio vaccine: fact versus fiction |journal=Vaccine |volume=22 |issue=15\u201316 |pages=1831\u20131835 |date=May 2004 |pmid=15121291 |doi=10.1016/j.vaccine.2004.01.028 }}</ref><ref name=PlotkinSA/> stating that:\n\n{{Quotation|at no time did I ever attempt to make cell cultures from chimpanzee tissues. In addition, I wish to state categorically that no poliovaccine was ever produced or could have been produced in Stanleyville, since the facilities were totally inadequate for the production or control of poliovaccine.<ref name=PlotkinSA/>}}\n\nIn his book, Hooper also stated that Gaston Ninane was involved in using chimpanzee cells to produce vaccine in Congo. Ninane responded to this allegation by stating that he could \"categorically deny\" ever having tried to make tissue cultures from chimpanzee cells.<ref name=Plotkin/> The people involved in vaccine production and distribution from America state that no vaccine was prepared locally in Congo and that only the CHAT vaccine from America was used. Barbara Cohen, the technician who was responsible for running the American laboratory that produced this vaccine stated:\n\n{{Quotation|At no time did I ever receive or work on chimpanzee kidneys, nor to my knowledge cells derived from chimpanzees. I never made, nor do I know of anyone in the lab who made polio vaccine in chimpanzee cells.<ref name=PlotkinSA>{{cite journal |author=Plotkin SA |title=Untruths and consequences: the false hypothesis linking CHAT type 1 polio vaccination to the origin of human immunodeficiency virus |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=815\u2013823 |year=2001 |pmid=11405925 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0861 |pmc=1088471}}</ref>}}\n\n== Scientific investigation ==\nThe OPV AIDS hypothesis has been examined and rejected by the scientific and medical communities as being unsupported or directly contradicted by available data, and inconsistent with HIV [[epidemiology]].\n\nIn an August 1992 letter published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', Koprowski repudiated the OPV AIDS hypothesis, pointing to multiple errors of fact in its assertions.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Koprowski |title=AIDS and the Polio Vaccine |journal=Science |volume=257 |issue=5073 |pages=1024\u20131027 |year=1992 |doi=10.1126/science.257.5073.1024 |pmid=1509249}}</ref> In October 1992, ''Science'' ran a story titled \"Panel Nixes Congo Vaccine as AIDS source,\" describing the findings of an independent panel which found each proposed step in the OPV-AIDS hypothesis \"problematic\". The story concluded:\n{{Quotation|...it can be stated with almost complete certainty that the large polio vaccine trial... was not the origin of AIDS.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Panel nixes Congo trials as AIDS source |journal=Science |volume=258 |issue=5083 |pages=738\u20139 |year=1992 |pmid=1439779 | doi=10.1126/science.258.5083.738-d  }}</ref>}}\n\nThe oldest confirmed sample of human tissue that shows the presence of HIV-1 is an archival sample of plasma collected from an anonymous donor in the city of Leopoldville, Belgian Congo (now [[Kinshasa]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]) in 1959 and was found with retrospective genetic analysis to be most closely related to subtype D strains. In 2008, partial HIV viral sequences were identified from a specimen of lymph node collected from an adult female, also in Kinshasa, in 1960. This specimen, named DRC60, was around 88% similar to ZR59, but was found to be most closely related to subtype A HIV-1 strains. These specimens are significant not only because they are the oldest specimens of the virus known to cause AIDS, but because they show that the virus already had an extensive amount of genetic diversity in 1960.<ref>Worobey M, Gemmel M, Teuwen DE, Haselkorn T, Kunstman K, Bunce M, Muyembe JJ, Kabongo JM, Kalengayi RM, Van Marck E, Gilbert MT, Wolinsky SM. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18833279 Direct evidence of extensive diversity of HIV-1 in Kinshasa by 1960.] Nature. 2008 Oct 2;455(7213):661-4.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the [[Royal Society]] held a meeting to discuss data on the [[AIDS origin|origin of AIDS]]; the OPV AIDS hypothesis was a central topic of discussion. At this meeting, three independent labs released the results of tests on the remaining stocks of Koprowski's vaccine, which Edward Hooper had demanded in ''The River''. The tests confirmed Koprowski's contention that his vaccine was made from monkey, rather than chimpanzee, kidney, and found no evidence of SIV or HIV contamination. Additional epidemiologic and phylogenetic data was presented at the conference which undermined other aspects of the OPV AIDS hypothesis. According to a report in ''Science'',<ref name=\"cohen0\">{{cite web |url= http://news.sciencemag.org/2000/09/vaccine-theory-aids-takes-blow|title= Vaccine Theory of AIDS Takes a Blow|last1= Cohen|first1= Jon|date= 12 September 2000|website= Science|access-date= November 2015}}</ref> Hooper \"did not challenge the results; he simply dismissed them.\"\n\nIn 2001, three articles published in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' examined various aspects of the OPV-AIDS hypothesis, as did an article published in ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]''. In every case, the studies' findings argued strongly against any link between the polio vaccine and AIDS.<ref name=\"blancou\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Blancou P, Vartanian J, Christopherson C, Chenciner N, Basilico C, Kwok S, Wain-Hobson S |title=Polio vaccine samples not linked to AIDS |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1045\u20131046 |year=2001 |pmid=11323657 |doi=10.1038/35074171}}</ref><ref name=\"berry\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Berry N, Davis C, Jenkins A, Wood D, Minor P, Schild G, Bottiger M, Holmes H, Almond N |title=Vaccine safety. Analysis of oral polio vaccine CHAT stocks |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1046\u20131047 |year=2001 |pmid=11323658 |doi=10.1038/35074176}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rambaut A, Robertson DL, Pybus OG, Peeters M, Holmes EC |title=Human immunodeficiency virus. Phylogeny and the origin of HIV-1 |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1047\u20131048 |year=2001 |pmid=11323659 |doi=10.1038/35074179}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Poinar H, Kuch M, P\u00e4\u00e4bo S |title=Molecular analyses of oral polio vaccine samples |journal=Science |volume=292 |issue=5517 |pages=743\u2013744 |year=2001 |pmid=11326104 |doi=10.1126/science.1058463|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ceae60b70620c6dd9d1089e129d4f17051423b66 }}</ref> The evidence cited included multiple independent studies that dated the introduction of HIV-1 to humans as occurring between 1915 and 1941, probably in the 1930s.<ref name=Korber>{{cite journal |author=Korber B |title=Timing the ancestor of the HIV-1 pandemic strains |journal=Science |volume=288 |issue=5472 |pages=1789\u201396 |year=2000 |pmid=10846155 |doi=10.1126/science.288.5472.1789 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Muldoon M |author3=Theiler J |display-authors=3 |last4=Gao |first4=F |last5=Gupta |first5=R |last6=Lapedes |first6=A |last7=Hahn |first7=BH |last8=Wolinsky |first8=S |last9=Bhattacharya |first9=T|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1231201 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Salemi M |title=Dating the common ancestor of SIVcpz and HIV-1 group M and the origin of HIV-1 subtypes using a new method to uncover clock-like molecular evolution |journal=FASEB J. |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=276\u20138 |year=2001 |pmid=11156935 |doi=10.1096/fj.00-0449fje |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Strimmer K |author3=Hall WW |display-authors=3 |last4=Duffy |first4=M |last5=Delaporte |first5=E |last6=Mboup |first6=S |last7=Peeters |first7=M |last8=Vandamme |first8=AM}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sharp PM, Bailes E, Chaudhuri RR, Rodenburg CM, Santiago MO, Hahn BH |title=The origins of acquired immune deficiency syndrome viruses: where and when? |journal=Philos. Trans. R. Soc. Lond. B Biol. Sci. |volume=356 |issue=1410 |pages=867\u2013876 |year=2001 |pmid=11405934 |doi=10.1098/rstb.2001.0863 |url=http://journals.royalsociety.org/openurl.asp?genre=article&issn=0962-8436&volume=356&issue=1410&spage=867 |pmc=1088480 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These results were confirmed by a later study using samples from the 1960s that also found that the epidemic began between 1908 and 1930,<ref name=Worobey2008>{{cite journal |author=Worobey M |title=Direct evidence of extensive diversity of HIV-1 in Kinshasa by 1960 |journal=Nature |volume=455 |issue=7213 |pages=661\u20134 |date=October 2008 |pmid=18833279 |doi=10.1038/nature07390 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Gemmel M |author3=Teuwen DE |display-authors=3 |last4=Haselkorn |first4=Tamara |last5=Kunstman |first5=Kevin |last6=Bunce |first6=Michael |last7=Muyembe |first7=Jean-Jacques |last8=Kabongo |first8=Jean-Marie M. |last9=Kalengayi |first9=Rapha\u00ebl M. |pmc=3682493}}</ref><ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web |url=http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnJOE491050.html |title=News Africa |work=Reuters.com |accessdate=2008-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005034208/http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnJOE491050.html |archivedate=5 October 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and a study that showed that although recombination amongst viruses makes dating less precise, it does not significantly bias estimates in either direction (it does not introduce a [[systematic error]]).<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lemey P |title=The molecular population genetics of HIV-1 group O |journal=Genetics |volume=167 |issue=3 |pages=1059\u201368 |date=July 2004 |pmid=15280223 |pmc=1470933 |doi=10.1534/genetics.104.026666 |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Pybus OG |author3=Rambaut A |display-authors=3 |last4=Drummond |first4=AJ |last5=Robertson |first5=DL |last6=Roques |first6=P |last7=Worobey |first7=M |last8=Vandamme |first8=AM }}</ref>\n\nThe author of one of the studies, [[evolutionary biologist]] Edward Holmes of [[Oxford University]], commented in light of the new evidence: \"Hooper's evidence was always flimsy, and now it's untenable. It's time to move on.\"<ref name=\"cohen2\">{{cite journal |author=Cohen J |title=AIDS origins. Disputed AIDS theory dies its final death |journal=Science |volume=292 |issue=5517 |pages=615a\u2013615 |year=2001 |pmid=11330303 |doi=10.1126/science.292.5517.615a}}</ref> An accompanying editorial in ''Nature'' concluded:\n{{Quotation|The new data may not convince the hardened conspiracy theorist who thinks that contamination of OPV by chimpanzee virus was subsequently and deliberately covered up. But those of us who were formerly willing to give some credence to the OPV hypothesis will now consider that the matter has been laid to rest.<ref name=Weiss>{{cite journal |author=Weiss RA |title=Polio vaccines exonerated |journal=Nature |volume=410 |issue=6832 |pages=1035\u20131036 |year=2001 |pmid=11323649 |doi=10.1038/35074222}}</ref>}}\n\nThe possibility that chimpanzees found near Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of Congo (formerly Stanleyville) were, indirectly, the true source of HIV-1 was directly addressed in a 2004 study published in ''Nature''. Here, the authors found that while SIV was present in chimpanzees in the area, the strain of SIV infecting these chimpanzees was [[phylogeny|phylogenetically]] distinct from all strains of HIV, providing direct evidence that these particular chimps were not the source of HIV in humans.<ref name=\"worobey\"/>\n\n== Current oral polio-vaccine campaign in Africa ==\nRumours that polio vaccines are unsafe disrupted the longstanding effort of the [[WHO]] and [[UN]] to achieve [[poliomyelitis eradication]] worldwide through use of the oral polio vaccine of [[Albert Sabin]], which is thought to be safe and effective by virtually all medical authorities. If this long-term public-health goal could be achieved, [[poliomyelitis]] would follow [[smallpox]] as the second eradicated infectious human disease. The OPV AIDS hypothesis relates only to the historical origin of AIDS, and its proponents have accepted the safety of the modern polio vaccines, but rumors based on a misunderstanding of the hypothesis exist,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/2070634.stm Nigeria Muslims oppose polio vaccination] ''BBC News'' 27 June 2002</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/03/20/international/asia/20polio.html?pagewanted=2 Rumor, Fear and Fatigue Hinder Final Push to End Polio] Celia W. Dugger and Donald G. McNeil Jr. ''New York Times'' 20 March 2006</ref> and those rumors are blamed in part for the recent failure to eliminate polio in [[Nigeria]].<ref name=Jegede>{{cite journal |author=Jegede AS |title=What led to the Nigerian boycott of the polio vaccination campaign? |journal=PLOS Med. |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=e73 |year=2007 |pmid=17388657 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.0040073 |pmc=1831725}}</ref>\n\nBy 2003, cases of poliomyelitis had been reduced to just a small number in isolated regions of [[West Africa]], with sporadic cases elsewhere.  However, the disease has since resurged in Nigeria and in several other nations of Africa, which epidemiologists trace to refusals by certain local populations to allow their children to be administered the Sabin oral vaccine. The expressed concerns of local populations often relate to fears that the vaccine might induce sterility,<ref name=BBC>BBC News (2005) \"Anti-polio vaccine Malians jailed\" [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4539757.stm online]</ref> and it seems that debate over the OPV-AIDS hypothesis has fueled additional fears.<ref name=Hooper1>Cohen, Jon (2000) ''[[Atlantic Monthly]]'' (Oct), p. 104.</ref> Since 2003, these fears have spread among some in the Muslim community, with Datti Ahmed, of the Supreme Council for Sharia in Nigeria stating that:\n\n{{quotation|\u201cWe believe that modern-day Hitlers have deliberately adulterated the oral polio vaccines with anti-fertility drugs and viruses which are known to cause HIV and AIDS.\u201d<ref name=Jegede/>}}\n\nPolio has also resurged in areas of Pakistan, India and Bangladesh.<ref name=GPEI>[[Global Polio Eradication Initiative]] (2007) Map of last six months of polio cases worldwide ''Wild Poliovirus Weekly Update'' initiative of WHO, CDC, UNICEF, Rotary International [http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casemap.shtml online] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20060925135122/http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casemap.shtml |date=25 September 2006 }}</ref><ref name=BBC2>BBC News (2007) \"Bangladesh begins new polio drive\" [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/6412835.stm online]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[AIDS origins opposed to scientific consensus]]\n*[[AIDS origin]]\n*[[SV40]] A scientifically accepted case of a monkey virus contaminating polio vaccine \u2013 Inactivated poliovirus vaccine (IPV) only.\n*[[Zoonosis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181743/http://www.cdc.gov/hiv/resources/qa/qa3.htm Where did HIV come from? Questions and Answers], from the United States [[Centers for Disease Control]]\n\n{{AIDS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Opv Aids Hypothesis}}\n[[Category:AIDS origin hypotheses]]\n[[Category:Vaccine controversies]]\n[[Category:Polio]]\n\n[[fr:Origine du virus de l'immunod\u00e9ficience humaine#La th\u00e9orie du vaccin anti-polio (en cours d'\u00e9laboration)]]\n", "name_user": "87.121.146.159", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OPV_AIDS_conspiracy_theory"}
